{
    "publish_date": "2014-02-04T17:03:28.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT4M8S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "Take a look out your window,", 
            "dur": "1.665", 
            "start": "7.789"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "put on your glasses if you wear them.", 
            "dur": "1.993", 
            "start": "9.454"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You might want to grab a pair of binoculars, too,", 
            "dur": "2.045", 
            "start": "11.447"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or a magnifying lens.", 
            "dur": "1.761", 
            "start": "13.492"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now, what do you see?", 
            "dur": "1.449", 
            "start": "15.253"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, whatever it is,", 
            "dur": "1.672", 
            "start": "16.702"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it&#39;s not the multiple layers of glass", 
            "dur": "1.878", 
            "start": "18.374"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "right in front of you.", 
            "dur": "1.291", 
            "start": "20.252"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But have you ever wondered", 
            "dur": "1.094", 
            "start": "21.543"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "how something so solid can be so invisible?", 
            "dur": "2.932", 
            "start": "22.637"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To understand that,", 
            "dur": "1.434", 
            "start": "25.569"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "we have to understand what glass actually is,", 
            "dur": "2.631", 
            "start": "27.003"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and where it comes from.", 
            "dur": "1.452", 
            "start": "29.634"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It all begins in the Earth&#39;s crust,", 
            "dur": "2.084", 
            "start": "31.086"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "where the two most common elements are", 
            "dur": "2", 
            "start": "33.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "silicon and oxygen.", 
            "dur": "2.054", 
            "start": "35.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "These react together to form silicon dioxide,", 
            "dur": "3.111", 
            "start": "37.224"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "whose molecules arrange themselves", 
            "dur": "1.854", 
            "start": "40.335"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "into a regular crystalline form known as quartz.", 
            "dur": "2.91", 
            "start": "42.189"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Quartz is commonly found in sand,", 
            "dur": "2.927", 
            "start": "45.099"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "where it often makes up most of the grains", 
            "dur": "1.977", 
            "start": "48.026"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and is the main ingredient in most type of glass.", 
            "dur": "2.776", 
            "start": "50.003"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Of course, you probably noticed that glass", 
            "dur": "2.169", 
            "start": "52.779"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "isn&#39;t made of multiple tiny bits of quartz,", 
            "dur": "2.556", 
            "start": "54.948"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and for good reason.", 
            "dur": "1.332", 
            "start": "57.504"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "For one thing, the edges of the rigidly formed grains", 
            "dur": "2.619", 
            "start": "58.836"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and smaller defects within the crystal structure", 
            "dur": "2.501", 
            "start": "61.455"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "reflect and disperse light that hits them.", 
            "dur": "2.714", 
            "start": "63.956"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But when the quartz is heated high enough", 
            "dur": "2.333", 
            "start": "66.67"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the extra energy makes the molecules vibrate", 
            "dur": "2.63", 
            "start": "69.003"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "until they break the bonds holding them together", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "71.633"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and become a flowing liquid,", 
            "dur": "1.882", 
            "start": "73.753"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the same way that ice melts into water.", 
            "dur": "2.337", 
            "start": "75.635"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Unlike water, though, liquid silicon dioxide", 
            "dur": "3.281", 
            "start": "77.972"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "does not reform into a crystal solid when it cools.", 
            "dur": "3.349", 
            "start": "81.253"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Instead, as the molecules lose energy,", 
            "dur": "2.671", 
            "start": "84.602"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "they are less and less able", 
            "dur": "1.558", 
            "start": "87.273"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to move into an ordered position,", 
            "dur": "2.004", 
            "start": "88.831"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and the result is what is called an amorphous solid.", 
            "dur": "2.693", 
            "start": "90.835"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "A solid material with the chaotic structure of a liquid,", 
            "dur": "3.996", 
            "start": "93.528"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which allows the molecules to freely fill in any gaps.", 
            "dur": "3.583", 
            "start": "97.524"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This makes the surface of glass uniform", 
            "dur": "2.167", 
            "start": "101.107"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "on a microscopic level,", 
            "dur": "1.721", 
            "start": "103.274"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "allowing light to strike it", 
            "dur": "1.445", 
            "start": "104.995"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "without being scattered in different directions.", 
            "dur": "2.729", 
            "start": "106.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But this still doesn&#39;t explain", 
            "dur": "1.522", 
            "start": "109.169"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "why light is able to pass through glass", 
            "dur": "2.632", 
            "start": "110.691"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "rather than being absorbed as with most solids.", 
            "dur": "2.892", 
            "start": "113.323"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "For that, we need to go all the way down", 
            "dur": "2.059", 
            "start": "116.215"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to the subatomic level.", 
            "dur": "1.736", 
            "start": "118.274"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You may know that an atom consists of a nucleus", 
            "dur": "2.544", 
            "start": "120.01"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with electrons orbiting around it,", 
            "dur": "1.979", 
            "start": "122.554"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but you may be surprised to know", 
            "dur": "1.695", 
            "start": "124.533"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that it&#39;s mostly empty space.", 
            "dur": "2.002", 
            "start": "126.228"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, if an atom were the size of a sports stadium,", 
            "dur": "2.793", 
            "start": "128.23"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the nucleus would be like a single pea in the center,", 
            "dur": "2.794", 
            "start": "131.023"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "while the electrons would be like grains of sand", 
            "dur": "2.586", 
            "start": "133.817"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in the outer seats.", 
            "dur": "1.919", 
            "start": "136.403"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That should leave plenty of space", 
            "dur": "1.284", 
            "start": "138.322"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "for light to pass through", 
            "dur": "1.219", 
            "start": "139.606"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "without hitting any of these particles.", 
            "dur": "2.085", 
            "start": "140.825"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So the real question is not", 
            "dur": "1.364", 
            "start": "142.91"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "why is glass transparent,", 
            "dur": "1.641", 
            "start": "144.274"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but why aren&#39;t all materials transparent?", 
            "dur": "3.251", 
            "start": "145.915"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The answer has to do with the different energy levels", 
            "dur": "3", 
            "start": "149.166"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that electrons in an atom can have.", 
            "dur": "2.858", 
            "start": "152.166"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Think of these as different rows of seats", 
            "dur": "1.731", 
            "start": "155.024"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in the stadium stands.", 
            "dur": "1.685", 
            "start": "156.755"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "An electron is initially assigned to sit in a certain row,", 
            "dur": "3.334", 
            "start": "158.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but it could jump to a better row,", 
            "dur": "1.989", 
            "start": "161.774"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "if it only had the energy.", 
            "dur": "1.877", 
            "start": "163.763"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "As luck would have it,", 
            "dur": "1.466", 
            "start": "165.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "absorbing one of those light photons", 
            "dur": "1.619", 
            "start": "167.106"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "passing through the atom can provide", 
            "dur": "1.781", 
            "start": "168.725"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "just the energy the electron needs.", 
            "dur": "2.185", 
            "start": "170.506"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But there&#39;s a catch.", 
            "dur": "1.5", 
            "start": "172.691"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The energy from the photon", 
            "dur": "1.29", 
            "start": "174.191"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "has to be the right amount", 
            "dur": "1.503", 
            "start": "175.481"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to get an electron to the next row.", 
            "dur": "2.252", 
            "start": "176.984"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Otherwise, it will just let the photon pass by,", 
            "dur": "3.253", 
            "start": "179.236"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and it just so happens that in glass,", 
            "dur": "2.035", 
            "start": "182.489"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the rows are so far apart", 
            "dur": "1.969", 
            "start": "184.524"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that a photon of visible light", 
            "dur": "1.863", 
            "start": "186.493"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "can&#39;t provide enough energy for an electron", 
            "dur": "2.208", 
            "start": "188.356"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to jump between them.", 
            "dur": "1.698", 
            "start": "190.564"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Photons from ultraviolet light, on the other hand,", 
            "dur": "2.416", 
            "start": "192.262"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "give just the right amount of energy,", 
            "dur": "1.916", 
            "start": "194.678"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and are absorbed,", 
            "dur": "1.166", 
            "start": "196.594"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which is why you can&#39;t get a suntan through glass.", 
            "dur": "3", 
            "start": "197.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This amazing property of being both", 
            "dur": "1.959", 
            "start": "200.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "solid and transparent has given glass many uses", 
            "dur": "3.252", 
            "start": "202.719"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "throughout the centuries.", 
            "dur": "1.373", 
            "start": "205.971"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "From windows that let in light", 
            "dur": "1.548", 
            "start": "207.344"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "while keeping out the elements,", 
            "dur": "1.416", 
            "start": "208.892"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to lenses that allow us to see both", 
            "dur": "1.952", 
            "start": "210.308"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the vast worlds beyond our planet,", 
            "dur": "1.668", 
            "start": "212.26"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and the tiny ones right around us.", 
            "dur": "2.172", 
            "start": "213.928"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It is hard to imagine", 
            "dur": "1.05", 
            "start": "216.1"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "modern civilization without glass.", 
            "dur": "2.528", 
            "start": "217.15"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And yet for such an important material", 
            "dur": "1.893", 
            "start": "219.678"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "we rarely think about glass and its impact.", 
            "dur": "2.818", 
            "start": "221.571"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It is precisely because the most important", 
            "dur": "2.27", 
            "start": "224.389"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and useful quality of glass is", 
            "dur": "1.777", 
            "start": "226.659"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "being featureless and invisible", 
            "dur": "2.046", 
            "start": "228.436"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that we often forget that it&#39;s even there.", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "230.482"
        }
    ], 
    "title": "Why is glass transparent? - Mark Miodownik", 
